{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"918fe319-144b-4c01-bdf0-69f5996f7d31","content":"Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span` of native-sized integers. Both `nint` and `nuint` work:\n\n```csharp\nSpan<nint>  a = stackalloc nint[4];   // ✓ works\nSpan<nuint> b = stackalloc nuint[3];  // ✓ works\n```\n\nThe test confirmed correct behavior — `nint.MaxValue` resolved to `9223372036854775807` (Int64.MaxValue on this 64-bit system) and `nuint.MaxValue` to `18446744073709551615` (UInt64.MaxValue). This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5, when `nint`/`nuint` became first-class unmanaged types eligible for `stackalloc`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"56653870-5a8f-4121-93e6-23dd883c1a3e","outputTokens":197,"requestId":"0409:1E6E:6C6FAB:803B4A:69F3FA89"},"id":"b28f1026-69f7-4ca0-9d0a-96e0cc0dc5f3","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:57:51.672Z","parentId":"04d582b3-8ed4-40a8-9cc5-a2e8ba5a6420"}
